Replace the single `await nextTick()` with two awaited nextTick calls, or use a watch with `flush: 'post'` and verify the ref is populated:
```js
watch(() => props.showClosed, async (val) => {
  if (val) {
    await nextTick()
    await nextTick()  // second tick ensures child v-if mount + callback ref have fired
    closedGroupRef.value?.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' })
  }
})
```
Alternatively, replace the callback ref pattern with a watchEffect that reacts when closedGroupRef becomes non-null, eliminating the timing dependency entirely.

In App.vue's toggleShowClosed, clear pulseGhost when the user opens the Closed column:
```js
function toggleShowClosed() {
  showClosed.value = !showClosed.value
  localStorage.setItem(SHOW_CLOSED_KEY, String(showClosed.value))
  if (showClosed.value && pulseTimeout.value) {
    clearTimeout(pulseTimeout.value)
    pulseGhost.value = false
  }
}
```
This ensures the animation is always tied to an actual status-change event visible to the user.
